960
00:47:07,191 --> 00:47:11,788
You know, I've never known
anybody named Millard before.

961
00:47:13,264 --> 00:47:14,527
You don't know me.

962
00:47:14,598 --> 00:47:16,123
That's true.

963
00:47:16,200 --> 00:47:19,830
But if I did,
I bet we'd be best friends.

964
00:47:19,904 --> 00:47:23,568
You know, I'm starting to understand
why Chapman wants to put you away.

965
00:47:24,942 --> 00:47:26,467
(TIRES SCREECHING)

966
00:47:35,353 --> 00:47:37,720
(YELLING IN SPANISH)

967
00:47:41,759 --> 00:47:43,488
Out, out, out, out!
Vamonos, Vamonos!

968
00:47:45,930 --> 00:47:47,261
(GROANING)

969
00:47:47,331 --> 00:47:48,924
JOSELITO: Now, now, vamanos!

970
00:47:48,999 --> 00:47:51,263
Come on, come on,
come on! Now!

971
00:47:52,803 --> 00:47:54,032
(YELLING IN SPANISH)

972
00:47:54,772 --> 00:47:56,638
Which one of you
is Rockford?

973
00:47:56,707 --> 00:47:59,335
Well, looks like we're gonna
go international. I'm Rockford.

974
00:47:59,410 --> 00:48:00,571
You come with us.

975
00:48:00,644 --> 00:48:02,635
No, he's not going anywhere.
This man is my prisoner.

976
00:48:02,713 --> 00:48:04,977
He's in the custody
of the FBI.

977
00:48:05,082 --> 00:48:07,449
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

978
00:48:11,021 --> 00:48:12,079
Lose the cuffs.

979
00:48:12,156 --> 00:48:13,646
Nuh-uh.

980
00:48:13,724 --> 00:48:16,853
You want me to do it?
You're liable to get hurt.

981
00:48:22,666 --> 00:48:23,997
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

982
00:48:24,068 --> 00:48:25,365
(LAUGHING)

983
00:48:26,103 --> 00:48:29,300
Okay, listen up.
This how it goes.

984
00:48:29,373 --> 00:48:32,741
You two are going to
walk over to the bus stop.

985
00:48:32,810 --> 00:48:35,006
When you get there,
you wait.

986
00:48:35,079 --> 00:48:36,979
You take the first bus
that comes along.

987
00:48:37,047 --> 00:48:39,038
That way, you get to live

988
00:48:39,650 --> 00:48:41,675
and you have a real
nice story to tell your kids.

989
00:48:41,752 --> 00:48:43,652
(MEN LAUGHING)
And this is not gonna happen.

990
00:48:43,721 --> 00:48:45,189
I represent the
federal government...

991
00:48:45,256 --> 00:48:48,590
Or I pop you, right here.
Your choice.

992
00:48:52,430 --> 00:48:53,795
You better start
walking, Millard.

993
00:48:53,864 --> 00:48:55,628
I'd go with you, if I could.

994
00:48:58,636 --> 00:49:00,934
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

995
00:49:01,338 --> 00:49:02,328
Nice suit, gringo.

996
00:49:25,329 --> 00:49:27,559
(ARGUING IN SPANISH)

997
00:49:51,622 --> 00:49:52,919
(SHOUTING)

998
00:50:29,760 --> 00:50:31,159
(SCREAMS)

999
00:50:32,129 --> 00:50:35,190
Do you have a problem with
the concept of private property?

1000
00:50:35,266 --> 00:50:36,427
No.

1001
00:50:37,601 --> 00:50:39,000
Good choice.

1002
00:50:40,971 --> 00:50:44,134
Well, you care for a taquito?

1003
00:50:44,208 --> 00:50:46,267
(LAUGHING) A taquito?

1004
00:50:46,343 --> 00:50:48,402
Yeah. I haven't eaten
in two days, Jess.

1005
00:50:48,479 --> 00:50:51,540
All I've had is about 10
gallons of genuinely bad coffee

1006
00:50:51,615 --> 00:50:54,380
that's now starting to
dissolve my stomach lining.

1007
00:50:54,451 --> 00:50:56,419
Need something in there
to soak up the acid.

1008
00:50:56,487 --> 00:50:58,683
Well, a taquito
should certainly do that.

1009
00:50:58,756 --> 00:51:00,224
ROCKFORD: Two taquitos.

1010
00:51:01,525 --> 00:51:03,357
So,
on the phone you said you were in trouble.

1011
00:51:03,427 --> 00:51:05,521
Yeah, that's me,
master of understatement.

1012
00:51:05,596 --> 00:51:07,690
Are you talking new
trouble? More trouble? What?

1013
00:51:07,765 --> 00:51:09,699
It doesn't seem possible,
does it?

1014
00:51:09,767 --> 00:51:10,859
Thank you.

1015
00:51:10,935 --> 00:51:12,198
Jim, the last time
I saw you,

1016
00:51:12,269 --> 00:51:13,737
the FBI had you
in handcuffs.

1017
00:51:13,804 --> 00:51:16,205
Yeah?
Well, they still do.

1018
00:51:16,273 --> 00:51:17,365
What happened?

1019
00:51:17,441 --> 00:51:19,102
Well, it's a
little complicated,

1020
00:51:19,176 --> 00:51:23,841
but Chapman can now add grand
theft auto to his list of charges.

1021
00:51:23,914 --> 00:51:25,905
You didn't steal a car
from the FBI.

1022
00:51:25,983 --> 00:51:27,382
It was either that
or be kidnapped.

1023
00:51:27,451 --> 00:51:28,680
(LAUGHS)

1024
00:51:29,620 --> 00:51:30,746
You know,
Rocky never understood

1025
00:51:30,821 --> 00:51:32,880
why you wanted to
be a private investigator.

1026
00:51:32,957 --> 00:51:34,652
I have to admit,
I don't either.

1027
00:51:34,725 --> 00:51:36,853
I don't know how you go
through that all the time.

1028
00:51:36,927 --> 00:51:39,521
You think this is
my average work day?

1029
00:51:40,364 --> 00:51:41,923
If it were,
I'd be dead in a week.

1030
00:51:41,999 --> 00:51:43,091
Where's the rental?

1031
00:51:43,167 --> 00:51:45,693
Around the corner,
end of the block.

1032
00:51:48,138 --> 00:51:50,869
It's not a rental.
I'm driving my own car.

1033
00:51:50,941 --> 00:51:52,841
That's no good.
I told you to rent one.

1034
00:51:52,910 --> 00:51:54,469
I can't leave you
without a car.

1035
00:51:54,545 --> 00:51:56,411
Well, I don't intend
to be left.

1036
00:51:56,480 --> 00:51:58,039
Then I don't intend
to take you with me.

1037
00:51:58,115 --> 00:51:59,947
Damn it, Jess,
I'm running from the cops,

1038
00:52:00,017 --> 00:52:02,679
the FBI,
and a cast of thousands.

1039
00:52:02,753 --> 00:52:05,518
I... I'm wanted for murder.

1040
00:52:05,589 --> 00:52:07,284
You could be charged
with aiding and abetting.

1041
00:52:07,358 --> 00:52:09,452
You could be looking
at serious time.

1042
00:52:09,526 --> 00:52:12,291
You don't like my terms,
you better call somebody else.

1043
00:52:12,363 --> 00:52:13,922
Oh, why don't you call
your friend Becker?

1044
00:52:13,998 --> 00:52:14,988
No, no, no, he's a cop.

1045
00:52:15,065 --> 00:52:16,829
He'd have to turn
you in, right? Yeah.

1046
00:52:16,900 --> 00:52:19,562
Oh. What about
your attorney, Beth?

1047
00:52:19,637 --> 00:52:21,366
(SMACKING LIPS) Wouldn't work,
either, would it?

1048
00:52:21,438 --> 00:52:23,805
Because as an attorney
she's an officer of the court,

1049
00:52:23,874 --> 00:52:25,899
and she'd have to
turn you in, too.

1050
00:52:27,177 --> 00:52:30,738
My, my, my, my,
we have a real predicament here, don't we?

1051
00:52:31,849 --> 00:52:33,442
I'll drive.
Okay.

1052
00:52:39,323 --> 00:52:41,553
JESS: Jim, I really think
this is a mistake.

1053
00:52:41,625 --> 00:52:44,322
I mean, the Highway Patrol
is always all over the place.

1054
00:52:44,395 --> 00:52:46,659
ROCKFORD: I'm not going
anywhere near the cove.

1055
00:52:46,730 --> 00:52:49,199
According to what, I hope,
is reliable information,

1056
00:52:49,266 --> 00:52:51,758
Angel should be
right along here.

1057
00:52:51,835 --> 00:52:53,530
Here, here it is.

1058
00:53:18,829 --> 00:53:20,228
This is a step up
for him.

1059
00:53:20,297 --> 00:53:22,959
His last place
had cardboard walls.

1060
00:53:23,033 --> 00:53:24,125
You sure he'll take you in?

1061
00:53:24,201 --> 00:53:25,532
I'm sure.

1062
00:53:27,404 --> 00:53:28,701
(DOORBELL CHIMING)

1063
00:53:30,774 --> 00:53:32,401
So, he must be
a really good friend.

1064
00:53:32,476 --> 00:53:36,606
Angel? He'd sell me by
the pound if he had a buyer.

1065
00:53:36,680 --> 00:53:38,045
He owes me.

1066
00:53:40,718 --> 00:53:42,846
Jimmy, what are
you doing here?

1067
00:53:42,920 --> 00:53:44,479
Who told you
how to find me?

1068
00:53:44,555 --> 00:53:45,750
It was Pastorelli,
wasn't it?

1069
00:53:45,823 --> 00:53:48,315
That guy doesn't know the
meaning of keeping his mouth shut.

1070
00:53:48,392 --> 00:53:51,760
This is my punishment for
even talking to that creep.

1071
00:53:51,829 --> 00:53:52,990
Did anybody see you
come in here?

1072
00:53:53,063 --> 00:53:55,031
Nobody saw us.

1073
00:53:55,099 --> 00:53:56,464
Okay. Well, just don't
stand around out here

1074
00:53:56,533 --> 00:53:58,365
waiting for some gardener
to make a positive I.D.

1075
00:53:58,435 --> 00:53:59,800
Get in, get in!

1076
00:54:03,841 --> 00:54:05,275
Angel, this is
Jess Wilding.

1077
00:54:05,342 --> 00:54:07,174
Who cares? It's not
like you're gonna stay.

1078
00:54:07,244 --> 00:54:09,144
ROCKFORD: Angel?
I can't hear you, Jimmy.

1079
00:54:09,213 --> 00:54:10,942
Can't, can't hear a word
you're saying.

1080
00:54:11,014 --> 00:54:12,812
Don't try to talk me
into nothing.

1081
00:54:12,883 --> 00:54:15,511
Every time I get something good going,
you show up.

1082
00:54:15,586 --> 00:54:16,917
You're like some giant cat

1083
00:54:16,987 --> 00:54:20,924
who's all the time leaving
dead rats on my doorstep.

1084
00:54:20,991 --> 00:54:22,356
What am I supposed to say,
thank you?

1085
00:54:22,426 --> 00:54:24,952
What do you think, I can't come up
with enough dead rats on my own?

1086
00:54:25,028 --> 00:54:26,655
What the hell
are you talking about?

1087
00:54:26,730 --> 00:54:29,427
You're hot, man.
You got that wanted smell.

1088
00:54:29,500 --> 00:54:32,265
You're all over the tube.
They got an APB out on you.

1089
00:54:32,336 --> 00:54:33,462
What, you didn't know that?

1090
00:54:33,537 --> 00:54:36,472
Well, that's one dead rat
I ain't getting nowheres near.

1091
00:54:36,540 --> 00:54:38,599
Just keeps getting better,
doesn't it?

1092
00:54:38,675 --> 00:54:40,666
Where's the TV?

1093
00:54:40,744 --> 00:54:41,905
Where is it, Angel?

1094
00:54:41,979 --> 00:54:43,469
I won't tell you.

1095
00:54:43,547 --> 00:54:46,312
You think I'm gonna let you
squat here watching television

1096
00:54:46,383 --> 00:54:48,374
while they're putting your
picture up in the post office?

1097
00:54:48,452 --> 00:54:50,420
You're making me an
accessory after the fact.

1098
00:54:50,487 --> 00:54:52,615
Well, look on it
as a refreshing change.

1099
00:54:52,689 --> 00:54:54,783
You're usually an
accessory before the fact.

1100
00:54:54,858 --> 00:54:56,189
Don't make me
call the cops, Jim.

1101
00:54:56,260 --> 00:54:59,230
I don't want to do that. It's
not like there's a reward out.

1102
00:54:59,296 --> 00:55:01,025
Why don't we
get out of here?

1103
00:55:01,098 --> 00:55:02,896
You heard what he said.

1104
00:55:02,966 --> 00:55:04,365
If there was a reward
out on you,

1105
00:55:04,434 --> 00:55:05,731
he'd turn you in
just like that.

1106
00:55:05,803 --> 00:55:08,465
Like you wouldn't. I love
these holier-than-thou types.

1107
00:55:08,539 --> 00:55:10,064
Where's the TV?

1108
00:55:14,111 --> 00:55:16,409
Is this the channel where
you heard about the APB?

1109
00:55:16,480 --> 00:55:18,471
Yeah, they keep cutting in
with these bulletins.

1110
00:55:18,549 --> 00:55:21,314
Like, who cares about some
guy nobody ever heard of

1111
00:55:21,385 --> 00:55:23,683
killing some other guy
nobody ever heard of?

1112
00:55:23,754 --> 00:55:24,949
Where's the remote?

1113
00:55:25,022 --> 00:55:26,114
I'll make
a deal with you.

1114
00:55:26,190 --> 00:55:28,056
Just hand it over, okay?

1115
00:55:28,125 --> 00:55:30,457
You stay here
until the next update,

1116
00:55:30,527 --> 00:55:32,894
and then when you're brought up to speed,
you're out of here.

1117
00:55:32,963 --> 00:55:34,761
I'll make a deal with you.

1118
00:55:34,832 --> 00:55:37,301
You hand me the remote
and I won't break your arm.

1119
00:55:38,535 --> 00:55:40,003
You're not making
any friends here today.

1120
00:55:40,070 --> 00:55:41,538
You know,
the next time you need me,

1121
00:55:41,605 --> 00:55:43,937
I just might not
be there for you.

1122
00:55:44,007 --> 00:55:46,499
You're not there
for me now, Angel.

1123
00:55:46,577 --> 00:55:48,238
It's on. It's a bulletin.
Turn on the sound.

1124
00:55:48,312 --> 00:55:50,110
FEMALE REPORTER ON TV:
...where the vehicle had been abandoned

1125
00:55:50,180 --> 00:55:51,443
at Sixth and Alameda.

1126
00:55:51,515 --> 00:55:55,474
The discovery was made by a
police officer on routine traffic control.

1127
00:55:55,552 --> 00:55:57,714
To recap this
late-breaking story,

1128
00:55:57,788 --> 00:55:59,847
private investigator,
James Rockford,

1129
00:55:59,923 --> 00:56:03,223
charged with the murder of
fellow investigator, Bud Monckton,

1130
00:56:03,293 --> 00:56:06,194
is being sought tonight by both
the Los Angeles Police Department

1131
00:56:06,263 --> 00:56:07,628
and the FBI.

1132
00:56:07,698 --> 00:56:09,860
At a news conference
held earlier today,

1133
00:56:09,933 --> 00:56:12,129
Captain Chapman
had this to say.

1134
00:56:12,202 --> 00:56:13,897
The murder apparently
resulted from

1135
00:56:13,971 --> 00:56:16,565
a longstanding
and bitter business rivalry.

1136
00:56:16,640 --> 00:56:18,904
Both Bud Monckton
and James Rockford

1137
00:56:18,976 --> 00:56:21,172
specialized in
low-end divorce work.

1138
00:56:21,245 --> 00:56:22,679
There was a history of
violence... How can he say that?

1139
00:56:22,746 --> 00:56:24,942
...between the men that ended
tragically... I don't take domestic cases.

1140
00:56:25,015 --> 00:56:26,449
...with the death of
Mr. Monckton.

1141
00:56:26,516 --> 00:56:29,110
I would ask any citizen
who sees this man

1142
00:56:29,186 --> 00:56:31,177
to report the sighting
to the police.

1143
00:56:31,255 --> 00:56:34,919
Under no circumstances should
anyone attempt to approach Mr. Rockford.

1144
00:56:34,992 --> 00:56:38,087
He may be armed,
and should be considered dangerous.

1145
00:56:38,161 --> 00:56:39,151
(REPORTERS CLAMORING ON TV)

1146
00:56:39,229 --> 00:56:40,856
That's a terrible picture.
Tell me.

1147
00:56:40,931 --> 00:56:43,161
Again, an all points bulletin has
been issued for James Rockford,

1148
00:56:43,233 --> 00:56:45,998
primary suspect in
the murder of Bud Monckton.

1149
00:56:46,069 --> 00:56:48,731
Now back to our regularly
scheduled programming.

1150
00:56:50,974 --> 00:56:52,874
What are we going to do now?

1151
00:56:52,943 --> 00:56:54,570
Damned if I know.

1152
00:57:01,418 --> 00:57:02,943
(SIGHING)

1153
00:57:08,992 --> 00:57:09,982
You all right?

1154
00:57:10,060 --> 00:57:11,084
Mmm-hmm.

1155
00:57:11,161 --> 00:57:13,528
Just decided to shut up
and be supportive.

1156
00:57:14,965 --> 00:57:16,126
You better go home, Jess.

1157
00:57:16,199 --> 00:57:19,829
What, and leave you here
all alone to have all this fun?

1158
00:57:19,903 --> 00:57:21,735
You know, I'm usually pretty
good at this sort of thing.

1159
00:57:21,805 --> 00:57:23,330
I mean, I make
my living at it.

1160
00:57:23,407 --> 00:57:25,774
But I don't know what
the hell's going on here.

1161
00:57:25,842 --> 00:57:27,469
Every time I think
I'm getting a fix on it,

1162
00:57:27,544 --> 00:57:29,273
it morphs into something
completely different.

1163
00:57:29,346 --> 00:57:31,371
What are you doing?
Did I say sit down?

1164
00:57:31,448 --> 00:57:32,813
Did I say,
make yourself comfortable?

1165
00:57:32,883 --> 00:57:34,214
You guys gotta
get out of here.

1166
00:57:34,284 --> 00:57:35,945
The welcome mat is not out.

1167
00:57:36,019 --> 00:57:37,953
Before you burn
this particular bridge,

1168
00:57:38,021 --> 00:57:39,284
you better make damn sure

1169
00:57:39,356 --> 00:57:40,482
you're not gonna
need it again,

1170
00:57:40,557 --> 00:57:42,889
because when it's gone, Angel,
it's gone for good.

1171
00:57:42,960 --> 00:57:44,826
Now, he threatens me.

1172
00:57:44,895 --> 00:57:47,887
This from a man who knows that
I'd give him the shirt off my back.

1173
00:57:47,965 --> 00:57:50,957
Why not? It doesn't belong to you,
and neither does this house.

1174
00:57:51,034 --> 00:57:54,902
All I'm asking for is a few
square feet out of a possible 5,000.

1175
00:57:54,972 --> 00:57:56,462
I can't do it, Jimmy.

1176
00:57:56,540 --> 00:57:57,974
I mean, it kills me
to say this,

1177
00:57:58,041 --> 00:58:00,510
but you guys gotta move it.
The caterer's here.

1178
00:58:00,577 --> 00:58:01,703
The caterer?

1179
00:58:01,778 --> 00:58:04,338
Nothing fancy. Pigs in the blanket,
a couple of dips.

1180
00:58:04,414 --> 00:58:06,178
But they want to
set up out here,

1181
00:58:06,249 --> 00:58:07,978
and now that you're among
America's most wanted,

1182
00:58:08,051 --> 00:58:09,416
well, they just
ain't gonna get it.

1183
00:58:09,486 --> 00:58:13,286
Angel, I wouldn't last
10 minutes out on the street.

1184
00:58:13,357 --> 00:58:15,553
Put me in the maid's room,
the garage.

1185
00:58:15,625 --> 00:58:17,719
Just till dark.
I'll take my chances then.

1186
00:58:17,794 --> 00:58:18,886
Oh, Jimmy!

1187
00:58:18,962 --> 00:58:21,192
Hey...
I'll owe you, Angel.

1188
00:58:21,264 --> 00:58:23,062
Wouldn't that make
a nice change?

1189
00:58:23,800 --> 00:58:25,529
Why me?

1190
00:58:25,602 --> 00:58:28,833
Because, deep down,
you're a really nice person.

1191
00:58:29,706 --> 00:58:31,105
I know that.

1192
00:58:34,644 --> 00:58:36,373
All right. Come on.

1193
00:58:38,448 --> 00:58:39,540
Now, when the party
gets rolling,

1194
00:58:39,616 --> 00:58:41,243
you got these types
that like to look around,

1195
00:58:41,318 --> 00:58:42,547
so I'm gonna
put you in the back

1196
00:58:42,619 --> 00:58:44,348
where there shouldn't be
too much foot traffic.

1197
00:58:44,421 --> 00:58:45,911
I know it's none of
my business, Angel,

1198
00:58:45,989 --> 00:58:47,252
but what are
you doing here?

1199
00:58:47,324 --> 00:58:48,985
You're living
like Donald Trump,

1200
00:58:49,059 --> 00:58:50,254
you're throwing
catered parties.

1201
00:58:50,327 --> 00:58:51,886
You can't afford
to give a party.

1202
00:58:51,962 --> 00:58:53,293
I can't afford
not to give one.

1203
00:58:53,363 --> 00:58:55,195
Invite the right people.
That's how deals are made.

1204
00:58:55,265 --> 00:58:56,596
That's how
careers are born.

1205
00:58:56,666 --> 00:58:58,600
Now, when it comes
to the caterer,

1206
00:58:58,668 --> 00:59:00,693
well, that's bare bones stuff,
like I said.

1207
00:59:00,771 --> 00:59:03,263
What costs is the hard stuff,
but I'm not serving that.

1208
00:59:03,340 --> 00:59:05,399
It's just wine and
name brand mineral water,

1209
00:59:05,475 --> 00:59:07,273
and Mr. Brophy's never
gonna know it's gone.

1210
00:59:07,344 --> 00:59:09,073
Mr. Brophy is
the owner here?

1211
00:59:09,146 --> 00:59:10,807
ANGEL: It's one of those
Mr. and Mrs.

1212
00:59:10,881 --> 00:59:12,747
You-Can-Go-To-Hell
divorce cases.

1213
00:59:12,816 --> 00:59:16,650
You see, Mr. Go-To-Hell said
that I should stay here on the pad

1214
00:59:16,720 --> 00:59:18,552
while he's in London
doing business.

1215
00:59:18,622 --> 00:59:21,489
He's afraid that Mrs.
You-Can-Go-To-Hell is gonna slip in

1216
00:59:21,558 --> 00:59:23,356
and slide off
with the family silver,

1217
00:59:23,427 --> 00:59:24,861
and he wouldn't
give her a pickle fork.

1218
00:59:24,928 --> 00:59:28,228
Is this where you're putting us,
huh? In this wine cellar?

1219
00:59:28,298 --> 00:59:30,266
Yeah, until dark.
That's our agreement.

1220
00:59:30,333 --> 00:59:31,630
How are we going to know
when it's dark?

1221
00:59:31,701 --> 00:59:33,135
There aren't any
windows in here.

1222
00:59:33,203 --> 00:59:34,295
Yeah, and no one'll
see you,

1223
00:59:34,371 --> 00:59:35,805
and no one's gonna
blow the whistle.

1224
00:59:35,872 --> 00:59:37,135
You want to lay low?

1225
00:59:37,207 --> 00:59:38,641
Don't get much lower
than this.

1226
00:59:38,708 --> 00:59:41,405
Here, chill.
Have some vino.

1227
00:59:41,478 --> 00:59:43,276
Mouton Rothschild?

1228
00:59:43,346 --> 00:59:46,839
1961. You're not serving this,
are you?

1229
00:59:46,917 --> 00:59:48,078
What's wrong with it?
Well, nothing.

1230
00:59:48,151 --> 00:59:51,610
It just goes for seven,
$800 a bottle.

1231
00:59:51,688 --> 00:59:52,917
What's the white
he's got?

1232
00:59:52,989 --> 00:59:55,253
Conti Montrachet, 1987.

1233
00:59:55,325 --> 00:59:58,522
Oh, hey, that only goes
for $800 a bottle on up.

1234
00:59:58,595 --> 01:00:01,428
That should go very nicely
with the pigs in a blanket.

1235
01:00:01,498 --> 01:00:03,057
Seems to me you've got
enough to worry about

1236
01:00:03,133 --> 01:00:05,033
besides what I choose
to serve at my party.

1237
01:00:05,102 --> 01:00:06,501
I just worry that
you're serving it

1238
01:00:06,570 --> 01:00:08,299
from somebody else's
wine cellar.

1239
01:00:08,371 --> 01:00:11,568
You pop just one of those corks,
Angel, it's grand theft.

1240
01:00:11,641 --> 01:00:13,803
You just run on down
to the police station,

1241
01:00:13,877 --> 01:00:15,140
and then you can
turn me in.

1242
01:00:15,212 --> 01:00:18,409
(CHUCKLES) Hey, maybe we can
do time together. Be like old times.

1243
01:00:18,482 --> 01:00:20,348
That is, until they drop
a pellet on you.

1244
01:00:20,417 --> 01:00:21,782
Chin-chin.

1245
01:00:26,356 --> 01:00:28,586
Regular Hallmark card,
isn't it?

1246
01:00:28,658 --> 01:00:30,990
Yeah, I'm almost tempted
to open one of these

1247
01:00:31,061 --> 01:00:33,723
if I didn't feel so sorry
for Mr. You-Can-Go-To-Hell.

1248
01:00:33,797 --> 01:00:37,529
You have no idea the damage
Angel can do without even trying.

1249
01:00:38,635 --> 01:00:41,070
Jim, I've been thinking
about this.

1250
01:00:42,539 --> 01:00:44,337
The police don't have
an APB out on me.

1251
01:00:44,407 --> 01:00:46,535
I'm not on any wanted list.

1252
01:00:46,610 --> 01:00:48,305
Why don't you tell me
what you would do

1253
01:00:48,378 --> 01:00:50,346
if you could do it,
and let me do it instead?

1254
01:00:50,413 --> 01:00:52,575
Oh, no, that's very nice,
I appreciate that, but nothing...

1255
01:00:52,649 --> 01:00:53,741
I'm a very capable person.

1256
01:00:53,817 --> 01:00:55,285
Capable has nothing
to do with it.

1257
01:00:55,352 --> 01:00:56,786
You don't know what
you'd be dealing with here.

1258
01:00:56,853 --> 01:00:58,184
Neither do I.

1259
01:00:58,255 --> 01:01:00,383
I know it got one man killed
and put me in a frame

1260
01:01:00,457 --> 01:01:02,482
I can't seem to break out of.

1261
01:01:02,559 --> 01:01:04,254
What are you suggesting?
That we just give up?

1262
01:01:04,327 --> 01:01:06,728
No. Well, hey, I don't know.

1263
01:01:06,796 --> 01:01:08,127
Damned thing
doesn't make any sense.

1264
01:01:08,198 --> 01:01:11,259
Everything makes sense if
you put the pieces together right.

1265
01:01:11,334 --> 01:01:12,358
Okay?

1266
01:01:12,435 --> 01:01:13,994
What's the first piece here?

1267
01:01:15,772 --> 01:01:18,901
Linda Gustavo,
she hires you.

1268
01:01:18,975 --> 01:01:21,444
Only it turns out
there is no Linda Gustavo.

1269
01:01:21,511 --> 01:01:23,036
You know, I've been
thinking about that.

1270
01:01:23,113 --> 01:01:26,481
I mean, she really put on
a convincing performance.

1271
01:01:26,550 --> 01:01:30,111
She conned me into taking a
job I swore I'd never go near.

1272
01:01:30,187 --> 01:01:31,450
An actress.

1273
01:01:31,521 --> 01:01:34,889
Well, enough of those running
around this town that could use a gig.

1274
01:01:34,958 --> 01:01:37,359
She could be the one
that dialed 911

1275
01:01:37,427 --> 01:01:40,226
and told the cops to look
in the trunk of my car

1276
01:01:40,297 --> 01:01:42,493
for the gun
they planted there.

1277
01:01:42,566 --> 01:01:44,295
But who hired her, and why?

1278
01:01:44,367 --> 01:01:45,926
I don't know.

1279
01:01:46,002 --> 01:01:49,666
But my gut feeling tells me it has
something to do with Felicidad Records.

1280
01:01:49,739 --> 01:01:51,833
I mean,
there's something weird about that company.

1281
01:01:51,908 --> 01:01:54,434
Mmm. Music-business word
is not uncommon.

1282
01:01:54,511 --> 01:01:56,536
No, no,
it goes beyond that.

1283
01:01:56,613 --> 01:01:59,139
Why is there
a huge framed photograph

1284
01:01:59,216 --> 01:02:01,981
of President Reagan
hanging in the executive john?

1285
01:02:02,919 --> 01:02:04,387
They're Republicans?

1286
01:02:04,454 --> 01:02:06,445
Clandestine Republicans?

1287
01:02:06,523 --> 01:02:09,151
Why wouldn't they hang it
in a place of honor?

1288
01:02:09,226 --> 01:02:12,252
Why do they have these
satellite photographs

1289
01:02:12,329 --> 01:02:16,926
of the rain forest or some damn
thing? And surveillance photos?

1290
01:02:17,000 --> 01:02:20,095
I don't know. Really confusing,
isn't it?

1291
01:02:20,170 --> 01:02:23,538
I'll tell you something else. There's
enough Latins running around in all this

1292
01:02:23,607 --> 01:02:26,736
to do a remake of one
of those old Fox musicals.

1293
01:02:27,944 --> 01:02:33,314
Whoever Linda Gustavo is,
she pointed me directly at Hector Gustavo.

1294
01:02:34,784 --> 01:02:37,776
Or Felicidad Records. Or...

1295
01:02:37,854 --> 01:02:39,549
Bud Monckton.

1296
01:02:39,623 --> 01:02:42,490
Yeah, you see? You see,
this whole Bud Monckton thing,

1297
01:02:42,559 --> 01:02:45,119
that's a real sour note
in all this.

1298
01:02:45,195 --> 01:02:49,393
I mean, the FBI should've never
even heard of a slimeball like Monckton.

1299
01:02:49,466 --> 01:02:53,494
They not only knew about him,
he had some information they wanted.

1300
01:02:54,571 --> 01:02:56,835
You sure you don't
have any aspirin?

1301
01:02:56,906 --> 01:02:58,704
I'm getting my headache
back again.

1302
01:02:58,775 --> 01:03:01,676
Forget your headache for now.
We're on to something here.

1303
01:03:02,779 --> 01:03:04,042
You want to tell me
what it is?

1304
01:03:04,114 --> 01:03:05,411
Bud Monckton.

1305
01:03:05,482 --> 01:03:06,972
You didn't know
Hector Gustavo,

1306
01:03:07,050 --> 01:03:08,643
you didn't know
Felicidad Records,

1307
01:03:08,718 --> 01:03:10,686
but you had a history
with Bud Monckton.

1308
01:03:10,754 --> 01:03:12,984
A violent history,
as Chapman would say.

1309
01:03:13,890 --> 01:03:18,191
Somebody wanted to off ol' Bud,
for reasons yet to be determined.

1310
01:03:18,261 --> 01:03:20,229
Put me in the picture,
you've got the perfect patsy.

1311
01:03:20,297 --> 01:03:22,425
That's not bad
for the IRS.

1312
01:03:22,499 --> 01:03:23,557
Thank you.

1313
01:03:23,633 --> 01:03:26,102
(EXHALES DEEPLY) I've had so
much coming at me from all directions,

1314
01:03:26,169 --> 01:03:28,638
I guess I went into
overload and shorted out.

1315
01:03:29,773 --> 01:03:31,002
I don't have any answers yet

1316
01:03:31,074 --> 01:03:32,735
but I know where to find 'em.

1317
01:03:32,809 --> 01:03:35,210
Six for the road. Service
door at the end of the corridor.

1318
01:03:35,278 --> 01:03:37,269
Turn out the lights. Adios.

1319
01:03:38,782 --> 01:03:40,477
Pigs in a blanket.

1320
01:03:40,550 --> 01:03:41,847
(LAUGHING)

1321
01:03:43,887 --> 01:03:46,219
Jim, who do you think
would want to kill Monckton?

1322
01:03:46,289 --> 01:03:47,723
Anybody that ever met him.

1323
01:03:47,791 --> 01:03:50,988
(CHUCKLES) No, you gotta
narrow it down a little bit for me.

1324
01:03:51,061 --> 01:03:52,722
Now, whoever
killed Monckton

1325
01:03:52,796 --> 01:03:54,457
is the person
who's framing you.

1326
01:03:54,531 --> 01:03:57,023
Well, it's beautifully
cold blooded, you know.

1327
01:03:57,100 --> 01:03:59,797
I mean, steal my gun,
use it on Monckton,

1328
01:03:59,869 --> 01:04:02,497
and plant it back on me.
Nothing personal.

1329
01:04:02,572 --> 01:04:04,040
I'm just in it
to take the fall.

1330
01:04:04,107 --> 01:04:06,007
That sounded
a lot like admiration.

1331
01:04:06,076 --> 01:04:10,309
Well, hey,
you'd almost have to admire anything

1332
01:04:10,380 --> 01:04:12,974
that's put together with that
much thought and precision.

1333
01:04:13,049 --> 01:04:15,211
It's put together
like a Swiss watch.

1334
01:04:15,285 --> 01:04:17,151
There's the murder weapon,
there's videotape

1335
01:04:17,220 --> 01:04:19,848
of the two of us wailing away
at each other in the hall,

1336
01:04:19,923 --> 01:04:23,450
more video tape from a security
camera at Monckton's house

1337
01:04:23,526 --> 01:04:27,929
clocking me in at 9:45, the night of
the murder, and never clocking me out.

1338
01:04:27,997 --> 01:04:28,987
Why not?

1339
01:04:29,065 --> 01:04:30,362
'Cause I left
by the back door.

1340
01:04:30,433 --> 01:04:33,232
Now, either he didn't have a
security camera on that door,

1341
01:04:33,303 --> 01:04:37,365
or it wasn't working. But anyway,
gunshots were heard at 10:30.

1342
01:04:37,440 --> 01:04:39,204
Now, I have nothing
to prove I was anywhere

1343
01:04:39,275 --> 01:04:41,243
but right there
pulling the trigger.

1344
01:04:42,746 --> 01:04:44,145
If I make it, I'll call you.

1345
01:04:44,214 --> 01:04:45,511
No, no, no, wait.
I want to go with you.

1346
01:04:45,582 --> 01:04:47,414
No, no. No, Jess. No,
Jess. Yes, I...

1347
01:04:47,484 --> 01:04:49,714
You can't afford to say no.
You don't have a car.

1348
01:04:49,786 --> 01:04:53,120
I will, just as soon as I hot
wire whatever's in the garage.

1349
01:04:53,189 --> 01:04:56,284
Hey, when you're in
as much trouble as I am,

1350
01:04:56,359 --> 01:04:58,123
it's really
kind of liberating.

1351
01:05:28,658 --> 01:05:30,683
(SIREN WAILING)

1352
01:05:44,674 --> 01:05:45,869
Damn.

1353
01:05:47,710 --> 01:05:49,474
CHAPMAN: You know
how lucky you are?

1354
01:05:49,546 --> 01:05:51,981
Well, no, Chapman.
Just how lucky am I?

1355
01:05:52,048 --> 01:05:54,745
Flight to avoid arrest when
you're wanted for a capital crime?

1356
01:05:54,818 --> 01:05:55,979
You could have been shot.

1357
01:05:56,052 --> 01:05:58,248
Well, you're handling your
disappointment well, I'll give you that.

1358
01:05:58,321 --> 01:06:01,154
You think of yourself as some
kind of great comic, don't you?

1359
01:06:01,224 --> 01:06:02,953
Well, you're not funny.
You've never been funny.

1360
01:06:03,026 --> 01:06:05,358
Oh, sure I have. You've just
never heard my best material.

1361
01:06:05,428 --> 01:06:06,827
I save it for
the dinner crowd.

1362
01:06:06,896 --> 01:06:08,990
Come on, let's get this over
with. It's been a long day.

1363
01:06:09,065 --> 01:06:11,534
And a busy one.
Two GTAs in six hours,

1364
01:06:11,601 --> 01:06:13,626
and the last one has
an interesting history.

1365
01:06:13,703 --> 01:06:17,003
It was reported stolen two weeks
ago by a Mrs. Lenore Brophy.

1366
01:06:17,073 --> 01:06:18,563
Her husband stole it,
not me.

1367
01:06:18,641 --> 01:06:20,075
And I have it
on very good authority,

1368
01:06:20,143 --> 01:06:22,441
he wouldn't
give her a pickle fork.

1369
01:06:23,913 --> 01:06:25,108
Jim...

1370
01:06:26,916 --> 01:06:28,384
We don't need you here,
Lieutenant.

1371
01:06:28,451 --> 01:06:31,716
Yes, I was just escorting
Mr. Rockford's counsel...

1372
01:06:31,788 --> 01:06:35,247
She knows the way. And when
did it become Mr. Rockford?

1373
01:06:35,325 --> 01:06:36,759
What happened to Jimbo?

1374
01:06:36,826 --> 01:06:37,987
You're here to see
if you can do anything

1375
01:06:38,061 --> 01:06:39,085
for your old buddy,
aren't you?

1376
01:06:39,162 --> 01:06:41,290
No, sir. I'm just
escorting Miss Davenport...

1377
01:06:41,364 --> 01:06:42,456
Van Sant.

1378
01:06:42,532 --> 01:06:45,991
Well, you can't do anything for him,
Becker, so don't even try.

1379
01:06:46,069 --> 01:06:49,198
Not if you give a damn about
your career in law enforcement.

1380
01:06:49,272 --> 01:06:52,503
Now, take a look. There's
a lesson to be learned here.

1381
01:06:52,575 --> 01:06:54,236
You know what
that lesson is?

1382
01:06:55,745 --> 01:06:57,736
Try "Crime doesn't pay.”

1383
01:07:01,284 --> 01:07:04,777
Hey, uh, thanks for
being here, I...

1384
01:07:05,555 --> 01:07:08,525
Nice dress. Maybe
not for this occasion.

1385
01:07:08,591 --> 01:07:10,559
Are you going to start
with me again?

1386
01:07:10,627 --> 01:07:12,026
I was at a dinner party.

1387
01:07:12,095 --> 01:07:13,859
Actually,
I was the hostess.

1388
01:07:13,930 --> 01:07:17,025
I had to walk out on my
husband and all my guests.

1389
01:07:17,100 --> 01:07:19,967
I used to eat dinner.
All the time.

1390
01:07:21,271 --> 01:07:23,137
What'd you serve?
Give me the menu.

1391
01:07:23,206 --> 01:07:24,901
Start with the
hors d'oeuvres.

1392
01:07:24,974 --> 01:07:28,911
Jim, you getting hysterical or
something? How do you feel?

1393
01:07:28,978 --> 01:07:32,073
Like Job
without the boils.

1394
01:07:32,782 --> 01:07:35,581
They ought to be popping
out any minute now.

1395
01:07:40,590 --> 01:07:43,958
That's 5, 10, 11

1396
01:07:44,027 --> 01:07:48,624
12, 25, 35, 36, 37.

1397
01:07:49,432 --> 01:07:51,560
That's $12.37.

1398
01:07:52,402 --> 01:07:54,632
Make you nervous walking
around with all that cash?

1399
01:07:54,704 --> 01:07:58,106
I want you to make a list of everything
that goes into that property envelope,

1400
01:07:58,174 --> 01:08:00,108
and ask the sergeant
to sign off on it.

1401
01:08:00,176 --> 01:08:01,337
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

1402
01:08:01,411 --> 01:08:02,469
Listen,
if I could just...

1403
01:08:02,545 --> 01:08:05,344
It means, the last time I was
a guest of this establishment,

1404
01:08:05,448 --> 01:08:08,577
a silver money clip went into
the envelope and never came out.

1405
01:08:08,651 --> 01:08:09,675
That's a lie.

1406
01:08:09,752 --> 01:08:12,084
That's not a lie, Chapman.
My complaint's on file.

1407
01:08:12,155 --> 01:08:14,214
Excuse me...
Shut up, Becker.

1408
01:08:14,290 --> 01:08:17,692
You accusing the police of
stealing your lousy money clip?

1409
01:08:17,760 --> 01:08:19,694
You're not listening, Chapman.
I didn't say that.

1410
01:08:19,762 --> 01:08:21,753
I said it disappeared,
that's all.

1411
01:08:21,831 --> 01:08:24,459
I'm just asking for a little backup
paperwork this time around.

1412
01:08:24,534 --> 01:08:25,558
Jim...

1413
01:08:25,635 --> 01:08:26,966
That's, uh, that's...

1414
01:08:27,036 --> 01:08:28,231
That's what?

1415
01:08:28,304 --> 01:08:30,363
You looking for
some more charges?

1416
01:08:30,440 --> 01:08:32,204
You've got too many
to deal with as it is.

1417
01:08:32,275 --> 01:08:33,834
Will you stop
antagonizing him?

1418
01:08:33,910 --> 01:08:35,105
What's the matter with you?

1419
01:08:35,178 --> 01:08:37,272
All right,
cut him loose, Chapman.

1420
01:08:38,414 --> 01:08:40,439
What?
I said cut him loose.

1421
01:08:40,550 --> 01:08:42,985
He's got a witness,
puts him at home at the time of the murder.

1422
01:08:43,052 --> 01:08:44,076
What witness?

1423
01:08:44,153 --> 01:08:48,386
A credible one, Captain.
Miss Wilding of the IRS.

1424
01:08:49,225 --> 01:08:51,717
I'm sorry. I would have
come forward sooner.

1425
01:08:51,794 --> 01:08:53,853
I just assumed that
you had all the facts

1426
01:08:53,930 --> 01:08:55,796
as a result of
your investigation.

1427
01:08:55,865 --> 01:08:59,130
Chapman never lets facts
clutter up a case he's on.

1428
01:08:59,235 --> 01:09:00,566
I'm sure there are
any number of people

1429
01:09:00,637 --> 01:09:02,196
that can corroborate me
on this.

1430
01:09:02,271 --> 01:09:05,730
The Sand Castle was open. There
were all kinds of cars in the parking lot.

1431
01:09:05,808 --> 01:09:07,503
And you say he got home when?

1432
01:09:07,577 --> 01:09:10,012
10:45. You see,
I was waiting for him,

1433
01:09:10,079 --> 01:09:12,411
so when he drove in,
I looked at my watch.

1434
01:09:12,482 --> 01:09:14,416
I decided it was a little
too late to barge in on him,

1435
01:09:14,484 --> 01:09:16,452
and I decided I'd come
back another time.

1436
01:09:16,519 --> 01:09:19,682
There's no way that Rockford could
have shot Monckton downtown at 10:30,

1437
01:09:19,756 --> 01:09:21,656
and get out to Paradise Cove
by 10:45.

1438
01:09:21,724 --> 01:09:23,715
Not even the way he drives.

1439
01:09:23,793 --> 01:09:25,727
Let's start by
losing the jewelry.

1440
01:09:25,795 --> 01:09:27,263
Why? You're not
going anywhere.

1441
01:09:27,330 --> 01:09:29,264
The hell I'm not.
The hell you are.

1442
01:09:29,332 --> 01:09:32,267
Chapman, can I see you
in here for a minute?

1443
01:09:41,944 --> 01:09:43,605
Let him go, Chapman.

1444
01:09:43,680 --> 01:09:45,444
But, sir, we have
the murder weapon.

1445
01:09:45,515 --> 01:09:47,142
His .38.
His prints all over it.

1446
01:09:47,216 --> 01:09:49,446
And he has an alibi
for the time of the murder.

1447
01:09:49,519 --> 01:09:51,317
Now, he could have
been set up, Chapman.

1448
01:09:51,387 --> 01:09:53,116
You cannot overlook
that possibility.

1449
01:09:53,189 --> 01:09:55,681
All right, all right,
maybe I can't make the murder charge stick,

1450
01:09:55,758 --> 01:09:57,590
but I've got
a laundry list that will.

1451
01:09:57,660 --> 01:09:59,754
Two GTAs,
flight to avoid arrest.

1452
01:09:59,829 --> 01:10:01,763
And the threat of
legal action.

1453
01:10:01,831 --> 01:10:04,061
You don't lighten up,
he's gonna go ahead with that suit.

1454
01:10:04,133 --> 01:10:05,726
You really want to take
that into open court?

1455
01:10:05,802 --> 01:10:07,395
It's gonna play like
a police vendetta,

1456
01:10:07,470 --> 01:10:09,529
and the department doesn't
need that kind of trouble.

1457
01:10:09,605 --> 01:10:12,131
Now, drop it, okay?
Just drop it.

1458
01:10:14,010 --> 01:10:17,776
Counselor, we will not be
pressing charges against your client.

1459
01:10:17,847 --> 01:10:20,407
Not this time. Becker,
get your friend out of the irons

1460
01:10:20,483 --> 01:10:22,884
and get him the
hell out of here.

1461
01:10:22,952 --> 01:10:24,283
Yes, sir.

1462
01:10:25,088 --> 01:10:26,556
(LAUGHS)

1463
01:10:30,593 --> 01:10:31,754
Do you mind
waiting for me?

1464
01:10:31,828 --> 01:10:32,954
I'd like to walk Beth
to her car.

1465
01:10:33,029 --> 01:10:34,326
Sure. I parked
in the police lot.

1466
01:10:34,397 --> 01:10:36,126
Bye, Beth.
Bye-bye.

1467
01:10:38,735 --> 01:10:41,067
I want to thank you for being there for me,
Beth.

1468
01:10:41,137 --> 01:10:42,195
Yeah.

1469
01:10:42,839 --> 01:10:44,364
I want you to bill me.

1470
01:10:44,440 --> 01:10:45,908
(LAUGHS) I will.

1471
01:10:46,776 --> 01:10:49,746
There were a lot of
people there for you tonight.

1472
01:10:49,812 --> 01:10:53,680
Becker and Jess.
She's a nice lady.

1473
01:10:53,750 --> 01:10:57,152
I thought that was one of
those politically incorrect words.

1474
01:10:57,220 --> 01:11:00,679
Yeah, well, it is. But I can
use it because I'm a woman.

1475
01:11:01,724 --> 01:11:05,024
Is she going to be
somebody serious?

1476
01:11:05,928 --> 01:11:08,090
Jess? She was Dad's friend.

1477
01:11:09,098 --> 01:11:10,566
She's your type.

1478
01:11:11,300 --> 01:11:13,701
Yeah, yeah, I know.

1479
01:11:13,770 --> 01:11:15,238
Let me ask you something.

1480
01:11:15,905 --> 01:11:21,071
If you were describing a
friendship you had with somebody,

1481
01:11:21,144 --> 01:11:23,476
would you refer to it
as a relationship?

1482
01:11:23,546 --> 01:11:25,981
You know,
using the word relationship

1483
01:11:26,048 --> 01:11:28,415
instead of friendship,
but mean friendship?

1484
01:11:30,386 --> 01:11:32,684
Why don't you just
ask her, Jim?

1485
01:11:33,589 --> 01:11:36,183
Forget it.
I'll call you tomorrow.

1486
01:11:36,259 --> 01:11:38,751
What's that mean?
Another four years,

1487
01:11:38,828 --> 01:11:41,559
or just until you need
an attorney again?

1488
01:11:44,300 --> 01:11:46,564
The town's full
of attorneys, Beth.

1489
01:11:47,703 --> 01:11:49,603
It was just an excuse
to call you.

1490
01:11:49,672 --> 01:11:51,436
I've been looking for one.

1491
01:11:51,507 --> 01:11:54,943
I wanted you back in
my life. I've missed you.

1492
01:11:58,915 --> 01:12:00,576
I missed you, too.

1493
01:12:04,086 --> 01:12:06,145
You know what
really threw me, Jim?

1494
01:12:07,423 --> 01:12:08,891
You were the one
who encouraged me

1495
01:12:08,958 --> 01:12:11,086
to write the damn book
in the first place.

1496
01:12:11,894 --> 01:12:13,726
And then to not
even read it...

1497
01:12:13,796 --> 01:12:15,127
I read it, Beth.

1498
01:12:15,198 --> 01:12:17,530
Oh, don't make it worse
by lying about it, Jim.

1499
01:12:17,600 --> 01:12:20,262
I'm not lying, Beth.
I read it.

1500
01:12:20,336 --> 01:12:22,532
Then why didn't you call me?

1501
01:12:25,374 --> 01:12:26,705
I didn't like it.

1502
01:12:28,211 --> 01:12:30,407
Well... I'm sorry, Beth.

1503
01:12:30,479 --> 01:12:32,072
I... I didn't know
how to tell you.

1504
01:12:32,148 --> 01:12:35,550
I... I didn't want
to hurt your feelings.

1505
01:12:38,387 --> 01:12:40,219
Well, say something.

1506
01:12:42,491 --> 01:12:44,084
That's so sweet.

1507
01:12:44,861 --> 01:12:47,421
(CHUCKLES) It's stupid,
but it's sweet.

1508
01:12:54,537 --> 01:12:57,507
If you don't call me tomorrow,
I'm gonna call you.

1509
01:13:19,362 --> 01:13:22,263
Well, you saved my life
in there, Jess.

1510
01:13:22,331 --> 01:13:24,095
Thank you doesn't
quite cover it.

1511
01:13:25,534 --> 01:13:27,161
God, I'm glad
that's over with.

1512
01:13:27,236 --> 01:13:28,829
It isn't over. Not yet.

1513
01:13:28,905 --> 01:13:30,202
We still don't know
who killed Bud Monckton.

1514
01:13:30,273 --> 01:13:32,139
I don't care who killed him.

1515
01:13:32,208 --> 01:13:33,903
That may sound
a little cold...

1516
01:13:33,976 --> 01:13:35,774
Sounds very cold.

1517
01:13:35,845 --> 01:13:37,973
I never liked the man.

1518
01:13:38,047 --> 01:13:39,242
I didn't like him
when I met him.

1519
01:13:39,315 --> 01:13:42,580
I spent 20 years not liking
him. He was pond scum.

1520
01:13:43,619 --> 01:13:46,179
May sound a little harsh,
but that's the way I feel.

1521
01:13:47,290 --> 01:13:50,521
Jim, what would happen if
the police arrested you again?

1522
01:13:50,593 --> 01:13:52,061
They won't. Yeah,
but what if they did?

1523
01:13:53,562 --> 01:13:56,031
And what if it ends up
in court?

1524
01:13:56,599 --> 01:13:58,363
You testify, and...

1525
01:13:59,268 --> 01:14:01,327
But that's just it, Jim,
I can't.

1526
01:14:02,772 --> 01:14:05,867
I can't testify under oath
that you were home by 10:45.

1527
01:14:07,343 --> 01:14:09,334
I didn't check my watch.

1528
01:14:09,412 --> 01:14:11,141
I wasn't waiting for you.

1529
01:14:11,213 --> 01:14:13,272
I wasn't anywhere
near Paradise Cove.

1530
01:14:16,319 --> 01:14:17,946
You...

1531
01:14:18,020 --> 01:14:19,112
Lied.

1532
01:14:26,929 --> 01:14:29,261
Want to check out
Bud Monckton's?

1533
01:14:45,381 --> 01:14:49,284
Well, there's gonna be some lock picking
involved. You may want to wait here.

1534
01:14:51,988 --> 01:14:53,387
(SIREN WAILING)

1535
01:14:55,825 --> 01:14:57,293
Now, don't get
your hopes up.

1536
01:14:57,360 --> 01:15:02,093
Monckton's isn't one of those
lofts that made Architectural Digest.

1537
01:15:02,164 --> 01:15:04,223
(EXHALES)
It's pretty bare bones.

1538
01:15:04,300 --> 01:15:06,701
Will the police still
have it sealed off?

1539
01:15:06,769 --> 01:15:09,170
I'm in so much trouble,
I don't really give a damn.

1540
01:15:10,373 --> 01:15:12,341
You sure you don't want
to wait in the car?

1541
01:15:12,408 --> 01:15:14,775
So far,
you're real clean on all this.

1542
01:15:14,844 --> 01:15:16,642
Are you trying to
make me nervous?

1543
01:15:16,712 --> 01:15:18,703
How are we going to
get into this place?

1544
01:15:18,781 --> 01:15:20,044
This way.

1545
01:15:31,894 --> 01:15:33,191
What about
the security camera?

1546
01:15:33,262 --> 01:15:36,994
I doubt if anyone's checking
them now that Monckton's gone.

1547
01:15:37,066 --> 01:15:40,400
But just in case,
I'll take care of them on the way out.

1548
01:16:00,589 --> 01:16:02,182
Watch your step.

1549
01:16:02,258 --> 01:16:05,785
His office is over here,
if that's what you want to call it.

1550
01:16:05,861 --> 01:16:09,388
If we're gonna find anything,
we'll find it here.

1551
01:16:10,199 --> 01:16:12,293
Don't you touch
anything, huh?

1552
01:16:12,368 --> 01:16:15,201
If you do,
be sure and tell me

1553
01:16:15,271 --> 01:16:18,104
so I can wipe your
prints off. Can you see?

1554
01:16:18,174 --> 01:16:20,165
I'm fine. Let's go.

1555
01:16:20,242 --> 01:16:21,732
You wait here.

1556
01:16:23,746 --> 01:16:25,009
(GASPS)

1557
01:16:26,082 --> 01:16:27,777
Oh, I'm sorry.

1558
01:16:27,850 --> 01:16:29,375
I guess I should
have warned you.

1559
01:16:29,452 --> 01:16:31,113
It kind of threw me
when I first saw it, too.

1560
01:16:31,187 --> 01:16:34,817
I thought his obsession was
reserved for electronic bugs.

1561
01:16:34,890 --> 01:16:36,016
Oh, God.

1562
01:16:36,625 --> 01:16:39,253
You don't think there's any around
here that aren't in cases, do you?

1563
01:16:39,328 --> 01:16:41,228
Not in his
appointment book.

1564
01:16:41,297 --> 01:16:42,594
Is that what
we're looking for?

1565
01:16:42,665 --> 01:16:43,826
Well, we're looking
for anything

1566
01:16:43,899 --> 01:16:46,425
that'll tell us who and
what he was mixed up with.

1567
01:16:46,502 --> 01:16:48,527
Felicidad Records,
for example.

1568
01:16:48,604 --> 01:16:51,630
You know,
record companies make big bucks.

1569
01:16:51,707 --> 01:16:54,438
Big bucks could mean
a mob connection.

1570
01:16:54,510 --> 01:16:56,774
They'd have the talent
to take him out

1571
01:16:56,846 --> 01:17:00,248
and fashion a very
nice frame for me.

1572
01:17:00,316 --> 01:17:01,715
Well, what can I do?

1573
01:17:02,918 --> 01:17:04,147
Want me to
check the computer?

1574
01:17:04,220 --> 01:17:05,688
You know how?

1575
01:17:11,127 --> 01:17:13,892
Where the hell's
his appointment book?

1576
01:17:13,963 --> 01:17:16,955
Everybody has to have some
kind of calendar to work from.

1577
01:17:17,032 --> 01:17:18,397
Well, it's probably
in here.

1578
01:17:18,467 --> 01:17:20,765
You said the guy
was into electronics.

1579
01:17:22,905 --> 01:17:24,100
Oh, yes.

1580
01:17:24,173 --> 01:17:27,108
He's got everything in here,
including his grocery list.

1581
01:17:29,078 --> 01:17:31,012
It's blank.

1582
01:17:31,080 --> 01:17:32,479
JESS: Well,
this is where it was.

1583
01:17:32,548 --> 01:17:33,879
It was erased, I guess.

1584
01:17:33,949 --> 01:17:35,849
Ah, that's just great.

1585
01:17:35,918 --> 01:17:37,682
Don't worry about it, Jim.
I'll get it back for you.

1586
01:17:37,753 --> 01:17:38,777
You said it was erased.

1587
01:17:38,854 --> 01:17:40,686
It is, but it's still
in there someplace.

1588
01:17:40,756 --> 01:17:42,451
I just have to find it.

1589
01:17:42,525 --> 01:17:44,789
(CHUCKLES) I'm IRS,
I do this all the time.

1590
01:17:54,703 --> 01:17:55,898
What'd I tell you?

1591
01:17:55,971 --> 01:17:57,029
(EXCLAIMING)

1592
01:17:57,106 --> 01:17:58,733
Scrolled ahead too far.

1593
01:17:58,807 --> 01:18:01,902
Can you scroll it back
till you come to an entry?

1594
01:18:01,977 --> 01:18:04,708
Got it! It's for tomorrow.

1595
01:18:04,780 --> 01:18:05,838
What does it say?

1596
01:18:05,915 --> 01:18:07,349
If you thought the FBI
connection was strange,

1597
01:18:07,416 --> 01:18:09,475
I don't know what you're
going to make out of this.

1598
01:18:09,552 --> 01:18:11,111
What does it say, Jess?

1599
01:18:11,187 --> 01:18:12,882
Jim, Monckton has
a luncheon meeting

1600
01:18:12,955 --> 01:18:14,946
scheduled for tomorrow

1601
01:18:15,024 --> 01:18:17,254
with Senator Phillip Aspall.

1602
01:18:21,363 --> 01:18:24,162
Oh, I think I better
keep that meeting.

1603
01:18:28,437 --> 01:18:30,132
ROCKFORD: Senator,
would you mind telling us

1604
01:18:30,206 --> 01:18:32,140
about your association
with Bud Monckton?

1605
01:18:32,208 --> 01:18:35,178
Well, I wouldn't call it
an association exactly.

1606
01:18:35,244 --> 01:18:37,178
I hired him to do
a job for me.

1607
01:18:37,246 --> 01:18:38,304
And the last time
I talked to him,

1608
01:18:38,380 --> 01:18:39,643
he told me he had
the information I needed,

1609
01:18:39,715 --> 01:18:42,275
but before
he could deliver it,

1610
01:18:42,351 --> 01:18:45,150
this terrible thing happened.

1611
01:18:45,921 --> 01:18:47,616
I take it
you're close friends?

1612
01:18:47,690 --> 01:18:49,385
Oh, not really close.

1613
01:18:49,458 --> 01:18:50,550
(LAUGHING)

1614
01:18:50,626 --> 01:18:52,390
Not really friends,
actually.

1615
01:18:52,461 --> 01:18:55,863
Well, both Mr. Monckton and
Mr. Rockford were private investigators,

1616
01:18:55,931 --> 01:18:59,629
so that just naturally gave
them a commonality of interest.

1617
01:18:59,702 --> 01:19:02,364
Well, I can certainly understand
how Mr. Rockford fits into the picture,

1618
01:19:02,438 --> 01:19:04,065
but Miss Wilding,
I hope you'll forgive me,

1619
01:19:04,139 --> 01:19:06,335
your place in it
somewhat eludes me.

1620
01:19:06,408 --> 01:19:09,673
If the CIA budget is out of
balance with the Congress,

1621
01:19:09,745 --> 01:19:12,578
I don't quite see how
the IRS gets into it.

1622
01:19:12,681 --> 01:19:13,807
CIA?

1623
01:19:13,882 --> 01:19:14,906
(CHUCKLES) Not that
we wouldn't welcome

1624
01:19:14,984 --> 01:19:16,884
all the help we can get,
you understand.

1625
01:19:16,952 --> 01:19:19,353
Excuse me.
You said the CIA.

1626
01:19:19,421 --> 01:19:21,753
Well, a proprietary
for the CIA.

1627
01:19:21,824 --> 01:19:24,555
Felicidad Records
is a front.

1628
01:19:24,627 --> 01:19:26,459
A prime example,
as far as I'm concerned,

1629
01:19:26,528 --> 01:19:29,930
of unnecessary
government expenditure.

1630
01:19:29,999 --> 01:19:32,661
They set up these
front organizations,

1631
01:19:32,735 --> 01:19:34,134
and they never
pull the plug on them,

1632
01:19:34,203 --> 01:19:37,696
and you and I have to go on
paying for that with our tax dollars

1633
01:19:37,773 --> 01:19:40,174
for the rest of
our natural lives.

1634
01:19:40,242 --> 01:19:42,939
I was elected on a platform
of fiscal responsibility,

1635
01:19:43,012 --> 01:19:45,208
and I'm damned well
gonna follow through on that.

1636
01:19:45,281 --> 01:19:47,511
Bud Monckton was investigating

1637
01:19:47,583 --> 01:19:50,416
Felicidad Records on your
behalf to put them out of business?

1638
01:19:50,486 --> 01:19:51,681
That's right.

1639
01:19:51,754 --> 01:19:55,452
And I could have, too, with the
information he promised me in his report.

1640
01:19:55,524 --> 01:19:57,959
Names, dates...

1641
01:19:58,027 --> 01:20:00,962
All the figures we weren't
able to get a hold of ourselves.

1642
01:20:01,030 --> 01:20:03,522
All the information,
all the facts that we needed

1643
01:20:03,599 --> 01:20:05,931
that we couldn't get
our hands on before.

1644
01:20:06,001 --> 01:20:08,197
Incredible waste there.

1645
01:20:08,270 --> 01:20:10,170
Have you ever seen
their offices?

1646
01:20:11,307 --> 01:20:13,139
(LAUGHING) I'm a
United States Senator.

1647
01:20:13,208 --> 01:20:16,769
I don't have an office anywhere
close to what Hector Gustavo has.

1648
01:20:18,080 --> 01:20:19,138
You know,
I've been going crazy

1649
01:20:19,214 --> 01:20:22,343
trying to figure out what this
is all about, and it's so simple.

1650
01:20:24,520 --> 01:20:26,488
It's the American Dream.

1651
01:20:27,589 --> 01:20:29,683
JESS: How can you say
a thing like that?

1652
01:20:29,758 --> 01:20:31,487
The American Dream?

1653
01:20:31,560 --> 01:20:33,426
I mean, Bud Monckton
was killed,

1654
01:20:33,495 --> 01:20:34,485
you were charged
with murder.

1655
01:20:34,563 --> 01:20:36,588
You could have spent the
rest of your life in prison.

1656
01:20:36,665 --> 01:20:39,999
There is a potential for
corruption in anything, Jess.

1657
01:20:40,069 --> 01:20:42,504
Even when it's painted red,
white and blue.

1658
01:20:42,571 --> 01:20:46,269
Nothing sinister about
the dream or the good life.

1659
01:20:46,342 --> 01:20:49,312
It's what some people will do to
achieve it you have to worry about,

1660
01:20:49,378 --> 01:20:52,040
and how far they'll go
not to lose it.

1661
01:20:52,147 --> 01:20:54,138
I'm afraid I have
a problem with this.

1662
01:20:54,216 --> 01:20:57,277
They just can't get by
with what they've done.

1663
01:20:57,353 --> 01:21:00,323
You thinking along the lines
of yearly audits?

1664
01:21:00,389 --> 01:21:02,255
If that's the best I can do.

1665
01:21:02,324 --> 01:21:04,554
Oh, I think we can do
better than that.

1666
01:21:09,798 --> 01:21:12,824
Hey, what the hell is...
Hey! What...

1667
01:21:12,901 --> 01:21:13,925
How many times
you been shot

1668
01:21:14,002 --> 01:21:15,094
for making a dumb move
like that?

1669
01:21:15,170 --> 01:21:17,434
I'm sorry, Dennis,
I didn't mean to freak you out.

1670
01:21:17,506 --> 01:21:20,373
I just wanted to check with you
one more time before you go in there.

1671
01:21:20,442 --> 01:21:22,103
So you've checked.

1672
01:21:22,177 --> 01:21:24,168
Are you sure you know
what you're gonna do?

1673
01:21:24,246 --> 01:21:26,078
Not really. In situations
where I can lose

1674
01:21:26,148 --> 01:21:29,083
both pension and credibility,
I'm more into improv.

1675
01:21:29,151 --> 01:21:30,516
Okay, okay.

1676
01:21:38,227 --> 01:21:42,061
Lieutenant Becker,
we have all been the souls of cooperation,

1677
01:21:42,131 --> 01:21:43,621
as far as I'm concerned.

1678
01:21:43,699 --> 01:21:45,531
We've made our statements.

1679
01:21:45,601 --> 01:21:48,093
I don't know why you need
anything further from us.

1680
01:21:48,170 --> 01:21:51,470
I'm investigating the murder of
an employee of yours, Mr. Gustavo.

1681
01:21:51,540 --> 01:21:53,099
Surely, you want us
to find the killer.

1682
01:21:53,175 --> 01:21:54,802
But you have.

1683
01:21:54,877 --> 01:21:58,211
That private investigator,
James Rockford.

1684
01:21:58,280 --> 01:22:00,180
It's been on the news,
in the paper.

1685
01:22:00,249 --> 01:22:01,808
Yeah, but you haven't
read the latest edition.

1686
01:22:01,884 --> 01:22:04,581
We thought we had a case,
it fell apart on us.

1687
01:22:04,653 --> 01:22:06,849
So now, we're back
to square one,

1688
01:22:06,922 --> 01:22:10,222
so we're going to do things
a little bit differently this time.

1689
01:22:10,292 --> 01:22:11,384
Is everybody here?

1690
01:22:11,460 --> 01:22:12,586
'Cause I want everyone.

1691
01:22:12,661 --> 01:22:15,255
Receptionists, secretaries,
maintenance, security.

1692
01:22:15,330 --> 01:22:18,163
Anybody that works
for Felicidad, in here.

1693
01:22:18,233 --> 01:22:19,257
Why?

1694
01:22:19,334 --> 01:22:20,597
Because I'm running
an investigation.

1695
01:22:20,669 --> 01:22:23,001
And that's the way
I want to do it.

1696
01:22:23,071 --> 01:22:25,130
All right,
but we have to leave somebody on security.

1697
01:22:25,207 --> 01:22:27,437
Won't be necessary, sir.
My men will make sure

1698
01:22:27,509 --> 01:22:30,206
that nobody goes in
and out of those offices

1699
01:22:30,279 --> 01:22:32,407
till your people
are back in place.

1700
01:22:33,382 --> 01:22:36,352
Now, I'm on a very tight schedule,
Mr. Gustavo.

1701
01:22:36,418 --> 01:22:39,513
I'd like to get out of here
as soon as possible.

1702
01:22:41,957 --> 01:22:44,756
BECKER: Now, the questions
will be very, very simple...

1703
01:23:16,658 --> 01:23:18,285
(EXCLAIMS SOFTLY)

1704
01:24:33,335 --> 01:24:36,430
(CLATTERING)

1705
01:24:43,879 --> 01:24:44,937
(GRUNTS)

1706
01:25:07,869 --> 01:25:09,598
I want men at every
possible exit,

1707
01:25:09,671 --> 01:25:11,400
out of sight,
low key as possible.

1708
01:25:11,473 --> 01:25:13,441
We don't want to give them
any indigestion.

1709
01:25:13,508 --> 01:25:15,499
You got it? Let's do it. OFFICER: Right,
Lieutenant.

1710
01:25:18,146 --> 01:25:19,375
You, I want out of here.

1711
01:25:19,448 --> 01:25:22,179
Chapman doesn't believe in cops
taking their buddies along on busts.

1712
01:25:22,250 --> 01:25:24,742
Hey, I'm the one that handed you the bust,
Dennis.

1713
01:25:24,820 --> 01:25:26,254
And if he ever
finds that out...

1714
01:25:26,321 --> 01:25:27,447
He won't.

1715
01:25:27,522 --> 01:25:30,753
You got an anonymous tip,
you got a court order, you found the tapes.

1716
01:25:30,826 --> 01:25:33,591
Stellar police work.
All I want is five minutes.

1717
01:25:33,729 --> 01:25:34,958
Why?

1718
01:25:35,030 --> 01:25:36,862
Because they lost, Dennis.

1719
01:25:36,932 --> 01:25:38,900
I want to rub
their noses in it.

1720
01:25:40,135 --> 01:25:41,660
You're on the clock.

1721
01:25:47,409 --> 01:25:48,399
May I help you?

1722
01:25:48,477 --> 01:25:49,638
No, I see my party.

1723
01:25:52,814 --> 01:25:54,179
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

1724
01:25:55,350 --> 01:25:57,182
(LAUGHING)

1725
01:25:57,252 --> 01:25:58,720
Well, well.

1726
01:25:58,787 --> 01:26:01,950
Eleanor warned you, Hector,
but here you all are.

1727
01:26:03,358 --> 01:26:06,293
When you're running
a rogue CIA operation,

1728
01:26:06,361 --> 01:26:10,958
having a regular table for lunch,
even at Rex's, is a really bad idea.

1729
01:26:11,033 --> 01:26:13,559
Do you know how many people
want to put you out of business?

1730
01:26:13,635 --> 01:26:16,536
There's me, of course,
Senator Aspall,

1731
01:26:16,605 --> 01:26:18,869
the Ways and Means
Committee,

1732
01:26:18,940 --> 01:26:21,739
the FBI,
the local constabulary.

1733
01:26:21,810 --> 01:26:24,575
Even the CIA wants
to tie a can to you.

1734
01:26:24,646 --> 01:26:27,377
Yet, we all know
right where to find you.

1735
01:26:27,482 --> 01:26:29,644
You can leave voluntarily,
Mr. Rockford,

1736
01:26:29,718 --> 01:26:30,810
or I can have you removed.

1737
01:26:30,886 --> 01:26:32,354
That always looks so awkward.

1738
01:26:32,421 --> 01:26:34,549
You know what
your major mistake was?

1739
01:26:34,623 --> 01:26:36,216
You fell in love
with your front.

1740
01:26:36,291 --> 01:26:38,282
That's all the record company
was meant to be.

1741
01:26:38,360 --> 01:26:39,725
It gave you
a legitimate excuse

1742
01:26:39,795 --> 01:26:41,661
to run around Latin America,

1743
01:26:41,730 --> 01:26:45,724
doing whatever clandestine
dirty work you were hired to do.

1744
01:26:45,801 --> 01:26:48,862
But show business
is very seductive.

1745
01:26:49,604 --> 01:26:52,801
You liked playing record mogul
and the hype and the glitz

1746
01:26:52,874 --> 01:26:55,366
a lot more than
you were supposed to.

1747
01:26:55,444 --> 01:26:57,640
You were willing
to murder to protect it.

1748
01:26:57,713 --> 01:26:58,908
Hector...

1749
01:26:58,980 --> 01:27:00,448
Well, I'm here to
tell you it didn't work.

1750
01:27:00,515 --> 01:27:02,745
You killed Monckton
for nothing.

1751
01:27:02,818 --> 01:27:07,153
You thought if the Senator didn't get
his report, he couldn't close you down.

1752
01:27:07,222 --> 01:27:09,850
Well, he doesn't have to.
The cops are gonna do it.

1753
01:27:09,925 --> 01:27:12,292
We had nothing to do
with Mr. Monckton's death.

1754
01:27:13,395 --> 01:27:16,524
Sure, you did.
You're amoral thugs.

1755
01:27:17,365 --> 01:27:20,335
You decided to off Monckton
the minute you had found

1756
01:27:20,402 --> 01:27:21,961
one of the bugs
that he hung on you.

1757
01:27:22,037 --> 01:27:24,096
Me, you found
in the newspaper.

1758
01:27:24,172 --> 01:27:27,039
That vivid account
of the stupid brawl

1759
01:27:27,109 --> 01:27:29,009
that we had after
the Goodhew Awards.

1760
01:27:29,077 --> 01:27:31,341
Not as vivid
as your imagination.

1761
01:27:31,413 --> 01:27:35,111
Oh, and the car full of Latinos
that you launched at me.

1762
01:27:35,183 --> 01:27:36,480
(CHUCKLES) What'd you do?

1763
01:27:36,551 --> 01:27:39,020
Did you con them
into believing that

1764
01:27:39,087 --> 01:27:42,057
they were doing something brave
and wonderful for their adopted country?

1765
01:27:42,124 --> 01:27:44,115
You promise them
another Bay of Pigs?

1766
01:27:44,192 --> 01:27:47,492
Oh, and the elusive
Linda Gustavo.

1767
01:27:47,562 --> 01:27:50,395
She's Linda Almeida. She's
doing dinner theater in Santa Fe,

1768
01:27:50,465 --> 01:27:52,729
How To Succeed In Business.

1769
01:27:52,801 --> 01:27:54,360
(SIGHING) You know,
Bud Monckton,

1770
01:27:54,436 --> 01:27:58,031
he was certifiably stupid
in every area but one.

1771
01:27:58,106 --> 01:28:00,473
Bugs. That was his obsession.

1772
01:28:00,542 --> 01:28:03,671
And the rumor is you didn't
find everything he hung on you.

1773
01:28:03,745 --> 01:28:06,680
The rumor is the cops found
a secret stash of tapes

1774
01:28:06,748 --> 01:28:10,275
that have you plotting his murder,
plotting my frame.

1775
01:28:10,352 --> 01:28:14,789
And the big rumor is you're
going away for a long, long time.

1776
01:28:15,857 --> 01:28:17,655
Have a nice lunch.

1777
01:29:03,405 --> 01:29:04,770
ROCKFORD: Hey, Jess!

1778
01:29:04,840 --> 01:29:06,467
Hi!

1779
01:29:06,541 --> 01:29:09,010
(CHUCKLES) Hi.
I wasn't expecting you.

1780
01:29:09,077 --> 01:29:10,738
I know. I should have
called first. Sorry.

1781
01:29:10,812 --> 01:29:11,973
No, that's not
what I mean.

1782
01:29:12,047 --> 01:29:14,607
I was out fishing.
I could've missed you.

1783
01:29:14,683 --> 01:29:15,912
You catch anything?

1784
01:29:15,984 --> 01:29:17,418
Nothing I wanted to keep.

1785
01:29:17,485 --> 01:29:18,611
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1786
01:29:18,687 --> 01:29:20,416
Well, this is for you.

1787
01:29:20,488 --> 01:29:21,546
What?

1788
01:29:21,623 --> 01:29:23,717
I mean, it's not exactly a present,
it's just...

1789
01:29:23,792 --> 01:29:25,521
Open it.
Okay.

1790
01:29:32,567 --> 01:29:35,002
Oh, a cuckoo clock.

1791
01:29:35,971 --> 01:29:37,905
You're right, you're right.

1792
01:29:37,973 --> 01:29:40,032
Rocky would have loved it.

1793
01:29:40,108 --> 01:29:41,974
Since he isn't with us,
I just thought,

1794
01:29:42,043 --> 01:29:44,137
|I don't know,
keep it in the family.

1795
01:29:44,212 --> 01:29:45,236
Well, thank you.

1796
01:29:45,313 --> 01:29:46,405
You're welcome.

1797
01:29:49,751 --> 01:29:51,150
(SIGHING)

1798
01:29:55,790 --> 01:29:57,087
You know,
you've never come out and said so,

1799
01:29:57,158 --> 01:29:59,923
but you want to know what
there was between Rocky and me.

1800
01:29:59,995 --> 01:30:01,724
No, no, I don't.

1801
01:30:05,000 --> 01:30:06,991
About six years ago, I...

1802
01:30:08,069 --> 01:30:11,300
I walked away from a fairly
disastrous relationship.

1803
01:30:11,373 --> 01:30:13,341
And unfortunately,
when I walked away,

1804
01:30:13,408 --> 01:30:16,867
I was left with this
very fragile ego,

1805
01:30:16,945 --> 01:30:22,679
and this inability to trust anyone,
and so much anger.

1806
01:30:25,320 --> 01:30:26,845
But, you know,
Rocky was so...

1807
01:30:26,922 --> 01:30:33,089
He was so warm, and funny,
and infinitely patient, and he healed me.

1808
01:30:36,197 --> 01:30:40,225
He was... He was the
grandfather that I never even knew.

1809
01:30:41,236 --> 01:30:44,331
He was my dad that I lost
when I was 12 years old.

1810
01:30:44,406 --> 01:30:50,209
He was my father confessor.
He was my best friend.

1811
01:30:51,413 --> 01:30:55,316
I'm going to miss him every day
of my life for the rest of my life.

1812
01:30:57,218 --> 01:30:59,209
He even taught me
how to fish.

1813
01:30:59,287 --> 01:31:00,755
(LAUGHS)

1814
01:31:00,822 --> 01:31:02,256
He taught me, too.

1815
01:31:05,327 --> 01:31:06,795
Hope you don't mind.

1816
01:31:06,861 --> 01:31:09,887
I mean, he let me think of
myself as part of his family.

1817
01:31:11,967 --> 01:31:13,298
But you...

1818
01:31:15,170 --> 01:31:17,969
You were the center
of his universe, Jim.

1819
01:31:18,039 --> 01:31:19,973
That never changed.

1820
01:31:20,041 --> 01:31:23,102
There was never a moment in
his life when you didn't come first.

1821
01:31:25,413 --> 01:31:29,680
I have a feeling that
you were a very close second.

